QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
(1) BLM adopts categorical exclusions to expedite geothermal energy permitt=
ing [ https://substack.com/redirect/5fcd9d55-a613-43f6-98d0-b6102f762865?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From the Bureau of Land Management
To improve permitting of geothermal energy exploration on public lands, the=
 Bureau of Land Management today adopted two existing categorical exclusion=
s from the United States Forest Service and the Department of the Navy. The=
 categorical exclusions will enable the agency to expedite the review and a=
pproval of geothermal exploration proposals.
I do not usually follow announcements from the Bureau of Land Management, b=
ut when Alec Stapp posted this on X [ https://substack.com/redirect/6671d0e=
9-c437-4cce-8c17-c34662aa003a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] it caught my attention. In a refreshing display of =
permitting reform, the agency adopted two categorical exclusions that would=
 streamline approvals for geothermal projects. Essentially, geothermal proj=
ects will not be subject to the same level of NEPA environmental review scr=
utiny as other large building projects. The exclusions also represent a imp=
ortant shift in how NEPA views geothermal, as such exclusions are only gran=
ted for =E2=80=9Cactivities that as a whole have been determined to pose no=
 significant risk to the quality of the human environment.=E2=80=9D
As a reminder, Geothermal energy is an abundant, clean renewable energy sou=
rce derived from our planet=E2=80=99s internal heat, which is harnessed by =
extracting hot water or steam from underground reservoirs in order to gener=
ate electricity. Geothermal does not produce much electricity in the U.S. t=
oday, due to high upfront costs, lack of land availability, and general env=
ironmental concerns (whether founded or not), but there=E2=80=99s been a re=
newed focus on its potential over the past couple of years from both the go=
vernment and private industry. Google and Microsoft are making bets on geot=
hermal which could eventually help power the insatiable demand for energy f=
rom their data centers. Back in November, we covered Fervo, a startup partn=
ered with Google, that is making a big swing at geothermal and is already o=
perational.=20
Geothermal is hot right now (ha) and probably the best thing the federal go=
vernment can do to support it is to just get out of the way. We=E2=80=99re =
all for the inclusion of more exclusions.=20
(2) CryoEM structures reveal how the bacterial flagellum rotates and switch=
es direction [ https://substack.com/redirect/138baed2-b85b-4aff-90f3-56a3cf=
1429fd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
My grandfather built motors that powered big machines. In a lab not so diff=
erent from his workshop, my colleagues and I uncovered the assembly of the =
bacterial motor. (Post on X [ https://substack.com/redirect/e4747d11-aec5-4=
8e9-a1af-563fcdb4488c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ])
With a better understanding of how bacteria move and orient themselves, we =
can develop new ways to prevent and treat infections. This new research fro=
m Prash and team, shows how a bacterial component called the C-ring functio=
ns in flagellar movement. The team used a technique called cryo-electron mi=
croscopy to observe the C-ring in two states, clockwise (CW) and counterclo=
ckwise (CCW), which are crucial for how bacteria move towards favorable env=
ironments.=20
Understanding this mechanism is crucial because bacterial movement (chemota=
xis) is closely related to their ability to cause diseases (pathogenicity).=
 The work could be used to developed targeted antibiotics, new vaccines, an=
d better diagnostic tools.=20
And that video is just mesmerizing to watch. =20
(3) AI traces mysterious metastatic cancers to their source [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/25484024-5590-4605-b637-648ee8028fc3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Smriti Mallapaty for Nature
Some stealthy cancers remain undetected until they have spread from their s=
ource [ https://substack.com/redirect/43273bbd-2060-401a-bef7-dfbb38298769?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to dis=
tant organs. Now scientists have developed an artificial intelligence (AI) =
tool that outperforms pathologists at identifying the origins of metastatic=
 cancer cells [ https://substack.com/redirect/75349920-5c41-4f9b-ade8-9fd43=
c98a9d0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] that circulate in the body1 [ https://substack.com/redirect/16646533-bfb6=
-46c2-b197-03e0f97e75dd?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. The proof-of-concept model could help doctors to improve=
 the diagnosis and treatment of late-stage cancer [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/3d49e9fd-7df7-4b31-8841-a45918b72628?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7G=
nA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and extend people=E2=80=99s lives.
We don=E2=80=99t think AI will fully replace doctors, but it will certainly=
 make the best doctors even better at doing their jobs. Research published =
this week describes an AI tool that effectively identifies the origins of m=
etastatic cancer cells, which are cancers that have spread from their initi=
al location to other parts of the body. About 5% of cancers today are metas=
tatic cancers whose origins are unknown. Understanding the origin helps doc=
tors determine proper treatment plans. =20
The AI had an 83% chance of accurately predicting the source of the tumor b=
ased on the images tested. Additionally, the AI model included the correct =
source of the tumor in its top three predictions 99% of the time. These res=
ults are a significant improvement over human pathologists. Accuracy improv=
ement is not only important because, uhh accuracy is important, but also be=
cause positive identification upfront prevents the need for additional and =
potentially invasive diagnostic tests.
Fuck cancer. Long live AI.
(4) Alphabet X=E2=80=99s Bellwether harnesses AI to help predict natural di=
sasters [ https://substack.com/redirect/986cde24-c9ec-4922-bac9-89e67fe116a=
3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Brian Heater for Tech Crunch
Bellwether is X=E2=80=99s moonshot to understand and anticipate changes acr=
oss the planet, so that any organization, community, or business can ask sm=
arter and more timely questions about the natural and built environment,=E2=
=80=9D project head Sarah Russell says in a social media post [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/29df2af8-85f9-454b-b6e7-34112c191687?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Q=
ifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. =E2=80=9CUntil now, it=
=E2=80=99s been epically hard and expensive to apply AI to geospatial quest=
ions, but our team has harnessed some of the most recent advances in machin=
e learning (plus some straight-up solid engineering) to re-think the whole =
endeavor.
First cancer. And now natural disasters. This AI can=E2=80=99t stop, won=E2=
=80=99t stop.
Alphabet's moonshot factory, X, launched Project Bellwether, a new initiati=
ve that uses AI to predict natural disasters such as wildfires and floods. =
Project Bellwether aims to improve disaster response times by enabling quic=
ker and more accurate predictions, improving first responder times and pote=
ntially saving lives and property. As some one who has yet to experience a =
big natural disaster (unless you count the New York City Earthquake of 2024=
!), I=E2=80=99m thankful Google is getting ahead of this. The climate is be=
coming more extreme and less predictable, so having AI carefully watching 2=
4/7 for what might happen next is only going to become more important. But =
those poor meteorologists may have to learn to code or something!
(5) Mark Zuckerberg - Llama 3, Open Sourcing $10b Models, & Caesar Augustus=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/540dee71-4112-4e93-8f57-b90bb5f099c3?j=3De=
yJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
When you get past this guy=E2=80=99s boyish good looks, you realize he=E2=
=80=99s actually saying some pretty profound stuff:
The Zuckaissance marched on this week, as a surfer-haired, chained-up Zuck =
went on Dwarkesh=E2=80=99s podcast to discuss the release of Meta AI, Llama=
 3, abundant energy and capex budgets, and the future of the metaverse. On =
top of its multi-hundred billion dollar core social media business and its =
infamous work on the metaverse, Meta is also quietly the potential leader i=
n AI =E2=80=94 at least from a strategic perspective. And with Meta=E2=80=
=99s core business humming, Zuck=E2=80=99s once-hated big bets starting to =
look in-the-money, and his personal approval skyrocketing, there=E2=80=99s =
likely not a more trending figure in the country right now than Zuck.=20
But why include this in the Weekly Dose? Does Zuck really need our praise, =
too? Well, I=E2=80=99ve shared this line of thinking before but I like when=
 our biggest builders are feeling themselves. It allows them to take bigger=
 swings =E2=80=94 with their money, resources, and reputations. And these a=
re the types of bets that can actually move the needle for humanity in a me=
aningful way. Zuck is suddenly cool? Awesome, maybe he=E2=80=99ll parlay th=
ose vibes into curing all diseases while also doubling down on that metaver=
se vision. (Actually, that=E2=80=99s exactly the goal of the Chan-Zuckerber=
g Initiative=E2=80=99s BioHub.)
Tesla stock up 10x in 5 years? Epic, Elon=E2=80=99s going to dump some of t=
hose gains into space exploration, brain machine interfaces, and freedom of=
 speech. Larry & Sergey have more money than they know what to do with? Per=
fecto, why don=E2=80=99t they sink that cash into moonshots like geothermal=
 and weather-predicting AI. You get the idea. We want our Worldbuilders out=
 there world building. Or at least that=E2=80=99s how I think about it.
Building hard things is good. We=E2=80=99re happy Zuck is getting the shine=
 he deserves.
Bonus: Five things to be optimistic about in America today [ https://substa=
ck.com/redirect/34a14523-8d94-4fb9-a353-45062ecc46b1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
From Noah Smith
Quick Spark Notes:
Crime Reduction: Violent crime rates, including murders, are decreasing acr=
oss the United States.
Climate Change Progress: Clean tech such as solar power and batteries have =
become economically viable, leading to reduced carbon emissions and a more =
optimistic outlook on managing climate change impacts.
Economic Growth: The U.S. economy is outgrowing other developed nations, fu=
eled by expansionary fiscal policies and a shift towards a more efficient a=
llocation of resources post-pandemic.
Generational Economic Improvement: Younger generations, particularly Millen=
nials and Generation Z, are achieving higher income levels and wealth compa=
red to their parents, aided by increasing house prices and decreasing debt =
levels. Who would=E2=80=99ve guessed that?
Reducing Wage Inequality: Wage inequality has decreased since the pandemic,=
 especially for low and medium-wage workers.
